<div id="review_13909578" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/13909578" />
    <a title="Colin Kinlund" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/83213-colin-kinlund"><img alt="Colin Kinlund" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1201134887p2/83213.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/13909578?book_show_action=true">Jan 28, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Colin Kinlund" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Colin Kinlund" href="/user/show/83213-colin-kinlund">Colin Kinlund</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer13909578" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12419758767370702065">I wanted to quote some verses from this book, but each line was made more beautiful by the one before it, and the one before that, until I’d have to include the whole book. And yet somehow the reverse effect is also true, in which the entirety of the mystic and divine collected in these pages is reflected in every word. Rumi writes: “The study of this book will be painful to those who feel separate from God.” But to read any one of these poems is to erase that separation completely. You that lov</span>
  <span id="freeText12419758767370702065" style="display:none">I wanted to quote some verses from this book, but each line was made more beautiful by the one before it, and the one before that, until I’d have to include the whole book. And yet somehow the reverse effect is also true, in which the entirety of the mystic and divine collected in these pages is reflected in every word. Rumi writes: “The study of this book will be painful to those who feel separate from God.” But to read any one of these poems is to erase that separation completely. You that love lovers, this is your home. Welcome!</span>
  <a data-text-id="12419758767370702065" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


